			<p class="first_paragraph">
				Would you classify this as an example of perceptual or mental subjectivity? Why? 
				Imagine this scene being shot from a more “neutral” perspective. Perhaps from a wide shot across the pool depicting Dustin Hoffman’s character, small and in the distance, walking out of the house and stepping into the pool. How would the scene be different for you as the viewer? What are you thinking and feeling with the subjective treatment that you wouldn’t be thinking and feeling with an objective treatment?
			</p>
			<p>
				We can classify this treatment as perceptual subjectivity since we see and hear things from Dustin Hoffman’s perspective. Note that we’re not privy to any internal thoughts of Hoffman’s character which would quality this as mental subjectivity. We’re only given access to his senses, not his mental processes. 
			</p>
			<p>

				I’d say that one thing the POV shot does for us is emphasize the alienation that Hoffman’s character feels from his family. As we see through his eyes and hear through his ears, we feel the intense separation from the outside world in a way that we wouldn’t if we were observing these actions from an external perspective.
			</p>

		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="videoContainer">		
		<div class="column firstColumn">
			<p>
				This next example from <em>Silence of the Lambs</em> demonstrates mental subjectivity (actual we get both perceptual and mental subjectivity in this scene). 
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="column secondColumn">
			<iframe src="//player.vimeo.com/video/73085324?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0&amp;color=ffffff" width="700" height="369" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="sectionContainer">
		<div class="three_sub_section section">

			<p class="first_paragraph">
				The mental subjectivity in this scene is the flashback that Jodie Foster’s character experiences while she observes a funeral. The funeral triggers a memory and we are given access to that memory, obviously information that we would not have if we were actually present at the funeral watching Jodie Foster observe the proceedings. 
			</p>
			<p>
				As we’ll see in a few weeks when we watch <em>The Silence of the Lambs</em>, Jonathan Demme makes periodic strategic use of perceptual and mental subjectivity and does so for very specific reasons that create a very different experience of the film than we’d get with a more “neutral” objective treatment.
			</p>
			<p>
				All these varying styles of narration are choices made by the film director who is trying to create the most effective distribution of story information––the distribution that succeeds in creating the desired series of effects in the mind and emotions of the viewer.
			</p>
			<p>
				There are a lot of variables involved in the way a director goes about chopping up and presenting the story material as a series of plot statements. But these categories that we’re delineating today represent some of the most frequent and significant decisions with the biggest impact on the viewer’s experience, and we’ll be referring back to these things frequently as we progress throughout the semester. 
			</p>
